The Data

The de-identified data consists of the following variables: parent's wealth quintile, child's wealth quintile, white (binary; whether the race of the person is white or not) and female (binary; whether the person's gender is female or not). We do not use female in the subsequent analysis.

df <- read.csv("../data/Data.csv")

df %<>%
  na.omit() %>%
  select(id, white, female, pwealthqn, wealthqn) %>%
  rename(
    quantile = wealthqn,
    pquantile = pwealthqn
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    id = as.factor(id),
    white = as.factor(white),
    female = as.factor(female),
    pquantile = as.factor(pquantile)
  ) %>%
  as.data.frame(.)

Model

Here, weve used an adjacent category model (family = "acat") for the ordinal logistic regression. However, I do not have a strong basis for choosing this family, and a cumulative logit model or other families for ordinal regression can be used as well.

\[ \begin{align} log(\frac{Pr(y_i = k)}{Pr(y_i = k+1)}) & = \alpha_k - \phi_i \\ \phi_i & = \beta_p P_i + \beta_r[k] R_i\\ \beta_p, \beta_r &\sim \textrm{Normal}(0, 1) \\ \alpha_k & \sim \textrm{Normal}(0,1) \end{align} \]

get_prior(quantile ~ pquantile + cs(white), data = df, family = "acat")

  data_grid(pquantile, white) %>%
